== Overview ==
Entity 87, commonly referred to as "backbugs," or by the scientific name ''Imitatae'' is an order of arachnids that rely on the backrooms for their life cycle and biological functions. Backbugs are often mistaken for other organisms due to anatomical differences, with each grouped into 5 families based on survival strategy and anatomy: ''Insidious Vermis'', ''Imitate Parasitus'', ''Insecta Celens'', ''Venator Inaturalist'', and ''Edentes Liminales''.

At agricultural levels, they are considered major pests and invasive species due to their more advanced adaptations relative to local predators. Backbugs are omnivores and decomposers and are most commonly found in entity-dense ecosystems; as such, they're considered by wanderers a sign of caution. Recently, health organizations such as the [[Backrooms Red Cross]] discovered many new enzymes within backbugs, which aid digestion and alleviate allergies.

== Biology ==
=== Insidious Vermis ===
{{Blurimage|file=House Centipede.png|caption=A backworm on the floor.}}
Insidious vermis (sneaky worms), colloquially called "backworms" or "concrete pests," are anatomically similar to roundworms and common insects, which, size-wise, range from 3 to 5 centimeters in length. Backworms have the ability to use a series of organs to shoot acid at 20 mph, with said acid being a mixture of corrosive acids, enzymes, water, and liquid pain, earning it a pH of 1.5. This acid serves as a deterrent mechanism against humans and entities, but is an important part of the backworm burrowing process as it softens concrete to the consistency of dirt. As such, the skin and muscle of backworms are made of material similar to that of mongooses, which have stomach acid with a pH of 1.4. Backworms have specialized muscles in their abdomens that slingshot them up to 11 mph in short bursts of energy. <ref>This muscle is theorized to be made of old vestigial legs.</ref>

Backworms are decomposers that feed off of dead and solid materials such as chalk because their digestive systems use the same acid to extract magnesium, iron, and calcium from the chemical structure. However, it's not their main source, as solid materials contain almost no nutrients. During backworm mating season, after mating, they stock up on nutrients to linearly no-clip through a select path to a safe level before dying. After 14 days, their eggs then hatch, and the baby worms consume their parent worm to gain the nutrients required for growth. Baby backworms use temporary wings to then linearly no-clip back toward other levels when they are mature, when their wings fall off.

=== Imitator Parasitus ===
{{Blurimage|file=EUUGHHH.png|align=left|caption=A Deathworm spotted during a colonoscopy.}}

Imitator Parasitus (Imitating Parasite), colloquially called deathworms, is a species of parasite anatomically and behaviorally similar to tapeworms, which feed off the nutrients of animals inside their digestive systems. Adult deathworms, after mating, camouflage their skin when predators approach, disguising themselves as their hosts' food. When an entity consumes the deathworm, the worm burrows into the entity's digestive system and lays eggs before dying. Then, when the baby worm hatches, they eat the parent worm, and gathers nutrients until adulthood, where they are excreted through feces. Then, as an adult, it will grow legs and search for a mating site. Some species of deathworm spend part of their life cycle inside a "filler creature" to then draw in a bigger main host once the previous host dies, either by natural causes or the fault of the deathworm.

They are especially known for their danger when a species of deathworm bursts out while the host is still alive, usually if it's housed in the wrong creature or using a wanderer as a filler creature. When this happens, the creatures will prematurely escape and burst out, perforating most organs in the host body, requiring extensive surgery to repair. As such, many drugs, like <ref> azeylomyfen, palononifior, karalazine, etc. </ref>, have been made to combat the spread of deathworm in humans. These programs have been a success, with the percentage of deathworm deaths decreasing by 90% in the past 10 years.

=== Insecta Celens ===
{{Blurimage|file=GiveThisThingABottlesWorthOfRaid.png|caption=A backpest specimen in captivity.}}

Insecta Celens (hiding insects), also referred to as backpests, have eight strong legs to burrow into any object and use it as a shell. They are separated from other members of the back-bug family by the fact that they have no anomalous properties. This survival strategy has worked well in their favor, making them very common in outdoor levels. They feed off dead material and plants, making them an essential part of the backroom's ecosystem. In recent years, many bug sprays (including Randevoos and Biocapacity) have been developed by organizations to combat the spread.

=== Venator Inaturalis ===
{{Blurimage|file=Spider.png|align=left|caption=A spilder after a meal, as hinted by the large abdomen.}}
Venator Inaturalists (unnatural hunters), also known as "spilders," are visually similar to the huntsman spider and are noted for their ability to camouflage and bend their bodies to hide. They hunt their prey by hiding as an object of desire and waiting until their prey arrives. They will then latch onto them and bite out a chunk of meat before running off. This strategy has allowed the species to hunt prey many times larger than themselves.

Biologically, spilders use a special fluid inside their bodies in which their organs are enclosed within flat, bony "sacks" attached to their legs that can compress and grow, though even with said sacks, they are very tiny, making the average spilder live for 9–12 months. Their mouths are large and flexible, with a ring of teeth and two large canines designed to grab large amounts of meat. The skin is composed of photoelectric cells, similar to those of an octopus, to camouflage itself.

=== Edentes Liminales ===
{{Blurimage|file=WORMS.png|caption=E. Liminales under a microscope in translucent dish soap.}}
Edentes Liminales (liminal eaters) are a set of microscopic back-bugs that have shrunk hundreds of times to feed off toxic materials in the backrooms (liquid pain, entity stomach acid, cashew water, etc.). Their bodies are worm-like, measuring 980 microns by 200 microns and feeding off nutrients in a host liquid or other extremophiles within the substance. Inside their bodies, they contain a skin resistant to said substance and a 'buffer layer' between the outside and inside of their bodies to filter out nutrients further. The digestive system of an E. Liminales consists of a series of small livers and stomachs that gain the most nutrients from the amount eaten.

E. Liminales are very commonly found in entity microbiomes, consuming nutrients such as bacteria and cleaning up excess compounds. These sterilization processes are also used to clean up waters contaminated with viruses and remove dirt before dying off when the proteins that support them run out.

== Behavior ==
The brains of backbugs are small and weak, so backbugs rely on special senses to navigate. Most back-bugs have the sense of akashicception, using small doses of a material deemed "Quaziline," which is composed of eye fluid, cashew water, and liquid pain. However, due to its recent discovery, most of its components are still unknown. Many also show signs of electroreception and enhanced senses.

== Discovery ==
Back bugs have been considered pests by [[Entity 70|Homo Callidus]], with many old cave paintings and a few collages depicting people squishing back pests and deathworm infections. Later, during medieval times, back-bugs were believed to be a product of the backroom adaptation of spontaneous generation. For example, it was believed that wanderers with Dearthworm infections were caused by a miasma rotting the host's body. Then, during the 1800s, backbugs were classified into their own species, and most of the knowledge about them comes from those times. In 1903, the family E. Liminales was discovered. In 1959, it was discovered that backbugs have electroreception and enhanced senses. Recently, on April 7th, 2025, their sense of akashic perception was discovered.

== Evolutionary History ==
Backbugs are believed to have evolved from Trigonotarbida<ref> Trigonotarbida are the first arachnids, resembling spiders</ref>that came into the backrooms; later, a species, deemed Arachnoides liminal, evolved the back part to be thinner and the head fatter, similarly to a millipede. They then branched out. For backworms, the legs evolved inward and became vestigial, with the family Venenum insontium developing venom glands before branching off into backworms and E. liminales.

Deathworms grow smaller, require fewer nutrients, and develop long life cycles, feeding on organic waste products. Backpests gained burrowing skills as part of their life cycle, and a mutation allowed them to continue doing so in adulthood, serving as a cover against predators. Spilders actually branched off from an earlier ancestor of A. liminales, keeping the fatter abdomen.

==Guide==

*When having ingested a parasite in this order, see your doctor and get prescription drugs such as azelomyfen and palonoifior.

*If you have noticed a high number of backbugs, stay away; it usually indicates a high level of entity activity.

*If you have been bitten by a spilder, disinfect the area; spilders contain a high number of bacteria.

